t908.text: Policy / regulatory analysis in many countries, including Australia, deeply craves and often legally requires modelling results so they can be weighed in cost benefit analysis - typically losing all nuance and qualifiers in the process. CGE models need to improve, but so do users

t909.text: Yes useless: most common use of CGE models in climate policy is to support or (mostly) discredit policies based on the specific numbers put out. But while relativities between policy scenarios may be meaningful, absolute numbers for cost v BAU are likely unreliably pessimistic.

t910.text: So are CGE models of climate policy, contradicted by real world data, useless? No and yes! Not useless: The dynamics they illustrate (like lower costs with equalized marginal abatement costs) are important, if worth also checking empirically.
